  {
    "id": "mock2018-q038",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "media-access-control",
    "stem": "In ______ each station sends a frame whenever it has a frame to send.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Pure ALOHA.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Slotted ALOHA.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Both (A) and (B).",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Neither (A) nor (B).",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Pure ALOHA and Slotted ALOHA both are the Random Access Protocols, that are implemented on the Medium Access Control (MAC) layer, a sublayer of Data Link Layer. The purpose of the ALOHA protocol is to determine that which competing station must get the next chance of accessing the multi-access channel at MAC layer. The main difference between Pure ALOHA and Slotted ALOHA is that the time in Pure Aloha is continuous whereas, the time in Slotted ALOHA is discrete.\n\nComparison chart: https://techdifferences.com/difference-between-pure-aloha-and-slotted-aloha.html",
    "explanationSource": "source",
    "referenceUrl": "https://techdifferences.com/difference-between-pure-aloha-and-slotted-aloha.html",
